        <p><strong>Borland C++</strong> is a {'C'|link_urls:'/l'}  and {'C++'|link_urls:'/l'}  programming environment ({'IDE'|link_urls:'i'}) for {'MS-DOS'|link_urls:'i'} and {'Microsoft Windows'|link_urls:'i'}.</p>
        <p>It was the successor to {'Turbo C++'|link_urls:'/l'}, and included a better debugger, the <strong>Turbo Debugger</strong>, which was written in protected mode DOS.</p>
        <p>Libraries</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>{'Object Windows Library'|link_urls:'i'} (OWL):</strong> A set of C++ classes to make it easier to develop professional graphical {'Windows'|link_urls:'i'} applications.</li>
            <li><strong>Turbo Vision:</strong> A set of C++ classes to create professional applications in {'DOS'|link_urls:'i'}. Those classes mimics some of the aspects of a Windows application like: dialog boxes, messages pumps, menus, accelerators, etc.</li>
            <li><strong>Borland Graphics Interface:</strong> A library of functions for doing simple, presentation-style 2D graphics. Drivers were included for generic CGA, EGA and VGA capability, with support for a limited number of video-modes, but more advanced, third-party drivers were also available.</li>
